In my course on Green Cities I always start the class on transportation planning by sharing with the students the result of a google news search I conduct the morning before class on the term <a href="https://www.google.com/search?hl=en&amp;gl=us&amp;tbm=nws&amp;authuser=0&amp;q=%22cyclist+killed%22&amp;oq=%22cyclist+killed%22&amp;gs_l=news-cc.3..43j43i53.1116.3313.0.3467.16.7.0.0.0.0.120.544.5j2.7.0...0.0...1ac.1.xuwVZTv_Br8">"cyclist killed."</a> There are always scores of articles documenting these tragedies throughout the United States and the world (today there were over 2000 hits).

The articles generally give the intersection or address where the fatality occurred and in class I bring up a google street view of the area and we discuss the specific problems relating to transportation planning that may have contributed to the fatality. Of course each accident is different and we usually don't know from the news article whether the driver was drunk or whether the cyclist was riding recklessly. Yet, in many of the sites clear problems like lack of bike lanes, streets engineered for high speeds and absence of sidewalks or shoulders are often observed.

